-- 
ITG, SuperGen, Titanium Metals, Validus: U.S. Equity Movers

-- B y   W h i t n e y   K i s l i n g
-- 
2011-07-13T18:38:54Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-12/electronic-arts-healthcare-services-udr-u-s-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
are having unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 2 p.m. in  New York .  Adtran Inc. (ADTN)   fell 8.8 percent to $36.60 and
slipped as much as 9.4 percent in the biggest intraday drop
since May 2010. The maker of high-speed digital transmission
products said third-quarter revenue will be unchanged to “mid-
single digits,” as compared with the second quarter.  Avid Technology Inc. (AVID)   climbed 5.4 percent to $20
and rallied 7.4 percent earlier in the biggest intraday advance
since March 18. The maker of software for digital audio and
video production was raised to “buy” from “hold” at
Brigantine Advisors.  Clean Energy Fuel Corp. (CLNE US) advanced 13 percent to
$17.03 after jumping to $17.21 earlier, the highest intraday
price since May 2. The builder and operator of natural-gas
fueling stations was boosted to “buy” from “underperform” at
Bank of America Corp. after receiving a $150 million investment
from Chesapeake Energy Corp. (CHK US).  Complete Production Services Inc. (CPX)   increased 6.5
percent to $36.79 and rallied 7.5 percent earlier, the most
intraday since May 18. The Houston-based oil and natural gas
company was raised to “buy” from “accumulate” at Global
Hunter Securities.  Investment Technology Group Inc. (ITG)   dropped 14
percent to $11.73 and earlier slipped 18 percent, the most
intraday since April 2009. The provider of securities trading
services reported second-quarter earnings will be no more than
15 cents a share, compared with the 20-cent average analyst
estimate. The company also said it was cutting jobs.  Kinetic Concepts Inc. (KCI)   rose the most in the Russell
1000 Index, climbing 5.7 percent to $68.15. The maker of wound-
care products and hospital beds said it will be acquired by a
group including private-equity firm Apax Partners LLP for $68.50
a share, or $4.98 billion in cash.  MedQuist Inc. (MEDH US) climbed 5.2 percent to $13.80
rising for the first time in five days. The electronic
transcription and health information provider had its price
estimate raised to $25 from $18 at Lazard Capital Markets, which
also reiterated its “buy” recommendation and said the
company’s acquisition of M*Modal will be a “transformational
transaction.”  Micron Technology Inc. (MU)   rose 4.3 percent to $7.62
and advanced 6.2 percent in the biggest intraday rise since
April 20. The largest U.S. maker of computer-memory chips was
rated a new “neutral” at MKM Partners LP, which said the
company is likely to “generate some cash.”  Midway Gold Corp. (MDW)   advanced 10 percent to $2.49 and
rallied to $2.53 earlier, the highest intraday price since April
2008. The gold mining company announced long gold intercepts at
its Spring Valley project.  News Corp. (NWSA)   climbed 4.4 percent to $16.03 and
rallied as much as 7.5 percent in the biggest intraday climb
since June 2010.  Rupert Murdoch ’s media company abandoned a 7.8
billion-pound ($12.5 billion) bid for full control of British
Sky Broadcasting Group Plc after allegations of phone-hacking
prompted an unprecedented political backlash. The shares had
fallen 15 percent from July 5 through yesterday.  SuperGen Inc. (SUPG)   climbed 3.4 percent to $3.05 and
earlier advanced 6.8 percent, the most intraday since June 16.
The drugmaker said its new drug application for Dacogen has been
accepted for review by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.  Titanium Metals Corp. (TIE)   rose 6.2 percent to $18.75
and rallied 6.3 percent earlier in the biggest intraday increase
since Jan. 26. The Dallas-based titanium-products maker had its
“buy” rating reiterated by D.A. Davidson & Co., which said
pricing trends for the company may be “overblown” and the
company is attractive because its stock has fallen.  Transcept Pharmaceuticals Inc. (TSPT)   fell the most in
the Russell 2000 Index, plunging 40 percent to $5.14. The Port
Richmond, California-based company said it failed to win U.S.
clearance for the first drug specifically designed to help
people get back to sleep after waking up in the middle of the
night.  Tuesday Morning Corp. (TUES)   declined 7.7 percent to
$4.19, the most intraday since June 15. The closeout home-
furnishing retailer said earnings for the year that ended June
30 were in a range of 21 cents to 23 cents a share, less than it
had forecast.  Validus Holdings Ltd. (VR)   fell the most in the Russell
1000 Index, sinking 8.1 percent to $28.30. The reinsurer offered
$55.95 a share to acquire  Transatlantic Holdings Inc. (TRH)  
and derail a planned merger with Allied World Assurance Company
Holdings AG. Transatlantic gained 4.7 percent to $51.34.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Whitney Kisling in New York at 
 wkisling@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
